@*
    Example 1 — Basic usage.

    The minimum viable select: a label, a themes directory, and a slug
    list. The select resolves "light" as the initial active theme (since
    "light" is in the list), sets data-theme="light" on <html>, and
    injects a <link rel="stylesheet"> pointing at /assets/themes/light.css.

    The status line is part of the pattern, not an extra. The control is
    an icon button: it shows only the ◑ glyph and its accessible name is
    always the Label ("Theme"), never the active theme name — so without
    this line neither a sighted user nor a screen reader can read the
    current selection back off the control. See docs/accessibility.md.

    aria-live="polite" announces mutations only, so this stays silent on
    first paint and speaks once on each subsequent change — exactly what
    a theme switch warrants (it is not an interruption).

    It is rendered visible on purpose: sighted users need the selection
    echoed too, and visible text helps cognitive accessibility. If a
    design genuinely cannot spare the space, keep the element and hide it
    with a visually-hidden (sr-only) class rather than deleting it — see
    docs/styling.md for the recipe.
*@

@page "/examples/theme-select/basic"
@rendermode InteractiveServer
@using LilyDesignSystem.Blazor.Helpers

<ThemeSelect
    Label="Theme"
    ThemesUrl="/assets/themes/"
    Themes="@Themes"
    @bind-Value="theme" />

<p class="theme-select-status" aria-live="polite">
    Active theme: @ThemeLabel(theme)
</p>

@code {
    private static readonly string[] Themes = new[] { "light", "dark", "abyss" };

    private string theme = "";

    // The component title-cases slugs for its own option labels; mirror
    // that here so the status line reads "Dark", not "dark". If you pass
    // a ThemeLabels dictionary to the select, look the label up in that
    // same dictionary instead so the two never drift.
    private static string ThemeLabel(string slug) =>
        string.IsNullOrEmpty(slug)
            ? "none"
            : char.ToUpperInvariant(slug[0]) + slug[1..];
}
